The bank said it was the first FTSE 100 company to make a public commitment to have women fill 40% of senior roles by 2020. LONDON - Lloyds Banking Group on Friday disclosed a gender pay gap of 32.8%, becoming the latest major British financial institution to say how the lack of women in senior roles is skewing average pay levels. The bank said it was the first FTSE 100 company to make a public commitment to have women fill 40% of senior roles by 2020. Royal Bank of Scotland on Friday disclosed a gender pay gap of 37%. Barclays this week disclosed a gap in its investment bank of 50%, drawing criticism from lawmakers. Royal Bank of Scotland on Friday disclosed a gender pay gap of 37%. Barclays this week disclosed a gap in its investment bank of 50%, drawing criticism from lawmakers.